<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / US Mid-Term Elections - November 8: California split over
anti-immigrant plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Opposition to California's Proposition 187, denying social services to
illegal immigrants, appears to be gathering momentum. Two new television
polls in the past 24 hours still left the initiative ahead, by 49-42 and
48-38 per cent respectively, but for the first time, it commanded less than
majority support and its edge was a far cry from the two-to-one margin
recorded a month ago.
Hispanic-American voters, in particular, have swung heavily against. A
survey released this week by the Southwest Voter Research Institute found 57
per cent opposed to the proposition, which is on the state ballot in next
Tuesday's mid-term poll, and only 15 per cent in favour, with the balance
undecided. In mid-October, polls showed nearly half the legal Hispanic
residents in support.
Opposition has also been fanned by the Mexican government. The foreign
ministry in September complained of the 'xenophobia and racism' implicit in
the proposal. Now Mexico is offering assistance and advice on fighting it to
Hispanic groups in California, a break with its practice of not interfering
in US politics.
Three Sundays ago, about 70,000 paraded in Los Angeles in protest, many
waving the Mexican flag - to the fury of the initiative's supporters. On
Wednesday about 10,000 schoolchildren, the majority Hispanic, walked out of
city classrooms to demonstrate.
Their teachers have also become vocal, with 1,000 signing a pledge to ignore
the provision in the proposition obliging them to report to the federal
government any case in which the parents of schoolchildren were suspected of
being illegal immigrants.
Several hospitals and medical associations have also threatened to refuse to
comply with the reporting provision, and have warned of the broader public
health consequences of denying care to illegal immigrants. Local chambers of
commerce, representing businesses with long histories of employing illegal
immigrants, remain generally opposed.
Mr Pete Wilson and Congressman Michael Huffington, Republican candidates for
governor and senator respectively, have remained steadfast in support of
Proposition 187, while their Democrat opponents, Ms Kathleen Brown and
Senator Dianne Feinstein, have campaigned against.
Mr Wilson's stand helped him move ahead of Ms Brown while the initiative
appeared to command broad support and has not hurt him since opposition to
it has grown. Mr Huffington, however, has been greatly embarrassed by the
disclosure that he had employed a British nanny without proper papers. One
poll out yesterday had Ms Feinstein 10 points to the good, but another had
Mr Huffington two points up.
Many other prominent state politicians have refused to take a position
either way. They include Mr Richard Riordan and Ms Susan Golding - very much
in the front line on immigration as mayors of Los Angeles and San Diego - on
the grounds that they do not want to encourage divisiveness in their cities.
Mr Dan Lungren, the state attorney-general locked in a tough re-election
battle, has also remained on the fence. On Monday he said he was 'legally
obliged' to defend Proposition 187 in the courts - lawsuits are inevitable
if it passes - but said he lacked the authority to prosecute teachers and
doctors for not reporting suspected illegal immigrants.
The movement against Proposition 187 may yet prompt a white suburban
backlash in its favour. As of now, it would probably pass, but Tuesday is a
long way off.
</TEXT>
