FT  04 NOV 94 / Swedish No voters lead poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The campaign to win Swedish entry to the European Union was jolted yesterday
when an opinion poll showed a swing against membership, in contrast to other
recent polls showing the Yes side set for a narrow win in the referendum on
November 13. The latest poll, in the newspaper Aftonbladet, gave the No camp
38 per cent support against 36 per cent in favour of membership. Most
worrying for the Yes campaign, led by the Social Democratic prime minister,
Mr Ingvar Carlsson, and strongly supported by most of Sweden's political and
industrial establishment, was the poll's finding that significantly more of
the 25 per cent of voters yet to make up their minds were more inclined to
vote No than Yes. The poll was cited by market dealers as the main factor
behind a sharp rise in long-term interest rates and a weakening of the
Swedish krona yesterday.
