<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Bosnian Croats take key town
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A heavy combined force of Bosnian and Croat soldiers yesterday overran the
strategic town of Kupres in central Bosnia, in a substantial setback for the
Bosnian Serb army.
It is the first important town the Bosnian Serbs have lost since the early
days of the 31-month war in Bosnia and raises fears the war will spread,
possibly forcing Serbia proper to come to their aid. The Kupres plateau,
dubbed the door to Bosnia, is of strategic importance for all three
communities. The joint offensive yesterday fuelled speculation that Croats
and Moslems could now fight each other over Kupres, which was 51 per cent
Serb and 39 per cent Croat before the war broke out.
UN officials last night confirmed the presence of regular Croatian army
units in the fighting for Kupres, which casts a shadow over any prospects
for progress in Serbo-Croat peace talks. Fresh talks between Croat officials
and rebel Serbs from Krajina, the self-styled state in Croatia, ended
yesterday in Knin, the Serb stronghold just over the border in neighbouring
Croatia, with little sign of progress towards agreement. Yesterday, cracks
appeared for the first time in the news blackout on the conflict imposed by
Serbia. Belgrade radio reported the Serb setbacks against the week-long
Moslem offensive which it had completely ignored. The end of the media
blockade signals mounting pressure on President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia
from the Yugoslav army and within his ruling Socialists to re-supply
Serb-held lands in Bosnia. The Bosnian Serbs have blamed the blockade
imposed by Serbia three months ago for their recent losses.
</TEXT>
