<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Rowland to quit Lonrho board: Defeat in bitter battle with
Bock marks the end of 33-year reign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tiny Rowland is to retire from the board of Lonrho, following a
protracted and bitter struggle with his fellow joint chief executive, Mr
Dieter Bock.
His departure after 33 years at the helm of Lonrho will remove from the UK
corporate scene one of its most controversial and charismatic characters.
Mr Rowland was once described by Mr Edward Heath, the former prime minister,
as the 'unacceptable face of capitalism', but created virtually from scratch
an international trading group encompassing mines in Africa, a chain of
international hotels and a complex web of other interests.
After two days of tempestuous negotiations between the warring chief
executives, Mr Rowland yesterday agreed to surrender his executive
responsibilities at the end of the year and to retire from the board
altogether in March.
If shareholders agree, he will then be given the honorific title of
president, allowing him to continue to visit African and Middle Eastern
heads of state in the company Gulfstream jet.
Mr Rowland, who is 76, has fought off previous attempts to remove him from
the company, but his colleagues said yesterday that the battle appeared to
have been won by Mr Bock. 'The papers are signed,' said one. 'It is a done
deal.'
According to a Lonrho director, Mr Rowland's reaction when told two days ago
that a majority of the board were in favour of his departure was 'I will see
you in hell first'. But it was made clear to Mr Rowland by the company's
chairman, Sir John Leahy, that 'he had no option'.
In the previous few days, Sir John - a retired diplomat who is only a
temporary chairman - had taken informal soundings from the board. Directors
were resolved to offer Mr Rowland the 'opportunity to make an elegant exit',
according to a financier.
However, they were equally determined that they would not take 'no' for an
answer.
Mr Rowland will continue to receive his salary of Pounds 1.24m, plus
expenses and benefits, until the end of next year. His 'benefits' last year
included Pounds 470,000 towards the costs of running his homes in London and
Buckinghamshire, and his expenses were more than Pounds 1m.
Mr Paul Spicer, a longstanding ally of Mr Rowland who retired from the
Lonrho board earlier this year said that his old friend had achieved one
significant victory. Under a new arrangement relating to Mr Rowland's 6.5
per cent shareholding in the company, Mr Bock - who holds 18.8 per cent - no
longer has the right to force Mr Rowland to sell him his shares on leaving
the company at the end of next year.
Mr Spicer said: 'He did not want to leave them (the shares) under the
control of Mr Bock.'
The contract paving the way for Mr Rowland's departure was signed by him at
4pm yesterday. It was then ratified by the company's board at a meeting
which began at 4.30pm and which Mr Rowland did not attend.
Mr Bock, who joined Lonrho at the beginning of 1993 when he bought his stake
in the company, has had an uneasy relationship with Mr Rowland for more than
a year.
He felt that his plans to reorganise Lonrho, which owns around 500
companies, were being frustrated by Mr Rowland.
Mr Bock launched an abortive coup two months ago to oust Mr Rowland. Hours
before September's board meeting, he backed off from proposing that Mr
Rowland should step down, fearing he could not count on the support of the
board.
Since then, two of Mr Rowland's closest supporters have resigned from the
board.
Lex, Page 16
How Bock turned the tables on Tiny, Page 19
</TEXT>
