<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / International Capital Markets: Four banks handle Portuguese
sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A four-bank consortium of Merrill Lynch, Banco Essi (the merchant banking
arm of Espirito Santo, one of Portugal's leading financial groups), UBS and
SG Warburg is to handle the sale of up to 30 per cent of Portugal Telecom,
which is likely to be the biggest global telecoms privatisation of next
year.
The deal will consist of four tranches, each handled by a different bank.
The domestic tranche, which will be listed in Lisbon, will be handled by
Banco Essi; the North America tranche by Merrill Lynch; the UK tranche by SG
Warburg and the rest of the world by UBS.
Between 20 per cent and 30 per cent of the company will be sold in the
initial public offering, which could raise between Dollars 1.2bn and Dollars
1.5bn. This would be Portugal's biggest privatisation and would value the
whole company at between Dollars 4bn and Dollars 5bn.
The offering is likely to take place in the second quarter of next year.
Three international banking consortia were consulted by the Portuguese
government to undertake a valuation of the company, which was formed by the
merger earlier this year of three state-owned telecommunications utilities
and is the country's biggest employer.
Portugal, which has about 34 telephone lines per 100 population, is expected
to open its telephone services to competition by 2003, five years after most
of the European Union.
