<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / International Company News: US hospital group rises on
improved margins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Columbia/HCA, the US's biggest hospital group, recorded a 14 per cent
increase in operating earnings in the three months to the end of September
on the back of a jump in out-patient services.
The company's operating profit margin improved to 18.6 per cent, from 17.9
per cent a year ago, said Mr David Vandewater, chief operating officer.
Columbia/HCA has pulled off a string of multi-billion dollar acquisitions in
the past 18 months in an attempt to bolster its market position and
strengthen profit margins at a time when healthcare companies across the US
are under pressure to reduce their prices.
The third-quarter figures reflect a 2 per cent increase in admissions at
hospitals which the company had owned a year before, and a 52 per cent
increase in out-patient visits.
While hospital stays are declining overall in the US, Columbia/HCA has
advanced in part by buying new hospitals in the same areas as its existing
facilities and then shifting patients between sites to boost admission
rates.
Operating profits for the period were Dollars 507m, up 14 per cent on a year
ago, while total revenues were Dollars 2.7bn, up 9.5 per cent.
Net income for the quarter was Dollars 153m, or 44 cents a share, after a
Dollars 23m charge for the early retirement of debt. The company reported an
after-tax loss of Dollars 56m, or 16 cents a share, in the 1993 period after
Dollars 193m of one-off charges.
The latest figures include some contribution from Medical Care America, an
acquisition of which was completed during September, but do not include
HealthTrust, which Columbia/HCA agreed to acquire after the end of the third
quarter.
</TEXT>
