<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / International Company News: Santa Fe turns down Union's
higher offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Santa Fe Pacific, the US railway company at the centre of a bidding war
between two other big US rail operators, yesterday said its board had
unanimously voted to reject an increased bid from Union Pacific and
reaffirmed its commitment to a friendly merger with Burlington Northern.
Last Sunday Union Pacific increased its hostile offer for Santa Fe to
Dollars 3.74bn, well above the value of an increased offer from Burlington
the previous Thursday. Burlington's all-share offer was last night worth
Dollars 3.08bn.
Santa Fe and Burlington continue to argue that the Union Pacific offer is
meaningless because it would almost certainly be ruled out on anti-trust
grounds.
They say that the Burlington offer, though worth less than Union Pacific's,
is much more likely to succeed.
