<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / International Company News: Deutsche Telekom sale to involve
US and UK banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN and ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The partial privatisation of Deutsche Telekom, expected to raise about
DM15bn (Dollars 10bn) in 1996, is likely to involve US and UK banks because
of the importance of both countries' stock markets, Mr Helmut Ricke, chief
executive, said yesterday.
He did not say which investment bank the state-owned telecommunications
company preferred for the main international role of global co-ordinator.
But it was important to give banks from the countries containing the world's
most important stock exchanges a decisive say in the share placement, he
said.
'That naturally applies to the US just as much as it does for Britain,' he
said. 'I can't imagine that there would be any political considerations
which would exclude a strong American partner. There is no disagreement
between management and the owners (the government) in this matter.'
Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank, is among the most likely candidates
to head the international placement, with Merrill Lynch, Salomon Brothers
and Morgan Stanley in the running, along with S. G. Warburg and Kleinwort
Benson from the UK.
Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank are expected to be named the overall
managers of the privatisation issue, which is likely to be split into
regional consortiums to cover Germany, the rest of Europe, North America and
the rest of the world.
A final decision is expected shortly, with banks standing to earn fees of
about DM450m from the placement.
However, Mr Ricke said a decision on which banks would be involved in the
issue would not be made as early as this week. 'We are under a certain
amount of time pressure but we will need to evaluate the matter more
carefully than that.'
Deutsche Telekom invited 22 of the world's leading investment banks to a
'beauty contest' in Bonn at which they presented their respective bids to
the company and the finance and postal ministries.
'They are all good,' Mr Ricke said. 'We now have to decide what their
particular strengths are, what connections they might have to companies
which we regard as our competitors.'
</TEXT>
