<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / International Company News: Consolidation in Italian banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The shape of Italian banking changed yesterday with a merger and takeover
which will further strengthen the private sector.
Ambroveneto is being taken over by Banca Commerciale Italiana (Comit) to
create the country's second largest banking group.
Comit last night said it wanted 51 per cent of Ambroveneto but would aim
initially for 29 per cent of the stock held by the core of controlling
shareholders. It offered L7,000 a share for the 144.4m shares among these
shareholders.
Meanwhile Credito Romagnolo (Rolo), a Bologna-based bank, is merging with
the Cassa di Risparmio di Bologna group (Caer), a regional savings
institution, to fight off the hostile bid by recently privatised Credito
Italiano.
The Rolo-Caer merger came as a surprise and will create Italy's tenth
largest bank. It comes less than a month after the two had abandoned
year-long talks on a smaller-scale merger.
The defensive move by Rolo, controlled by a core of shareholders led by Mr
Carlo De Benedetti, the Olivetti chairman, will have to overcome complex
legal considerations, centring on whether a merger could occur while a
takeover bid was in progress.
The formal takeover by Credito Italiano cannot be launched until the
prospectus has been approved by Consob, the stock exchange watchdog. This is
unlikely to be completed until November 15 and could mean that the first
extraordinary meeting of Rolo shareholders will vote not on the takeover
offer but the merger.
Rolo's big shareholders, including France's BNP and Mr De Benedetti, have
yet to comment on the merger plan.
The L2,010bn (Dollars 1.3bn) Credito bid for 48.2 per cent of Rolo's stock,
valuing each share at L19,000, was launched last Wednesday and is the
largest in Italy since new takeover rules were introduced in 1992.
It followed three weeks of heavy trading in Rolo shares which rose more than
30 per cent. But the Bologna bank denied any prior discussions with Credito,
claiming the bid was hostile.
Rolo's decision comes after the appointment of foreign advisers Goldman
Sachs International and Morgan Stanley to assess the takeover. Rolo said
yesterday the merger, which would be cashless, would be on the basis of 1.31
of its nominal L1,000 shares for every nominal L10,000 Caer share.
Rolo said it was currently valued at L4,895bn. This is a premium of about
L3,000 a share on the Credito offer and applies to all the shares, not just
48.2 per cent. Caer was valued at L2,397bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Banco Ambrosiano Veneto.
    Banca Commerciale Italiana.
    Credito Romagnolo.
    Cassa di Risparmio di Bologna.
</CO>
