<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Quaker buys 'new age' drinks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Quaker Oats, the US food and beverage group, has agreed to pay Dollars 1.7bn
(Pounds 1.07bn) in cash to acquire Snapple Beverage, a company that has
changed the shape of the US soft drinks market with its 'new age' iced teas
and fruit-flavoured drinks.
Quaker also said it would seek buyers for its European petfood business,
which makes Felix catfood and Fido dogfood, and its Mexican confectionery
arm which produces La Azteca chocolate.
Snapple, based in Valley Stream, Long Island, has grown rapidly in the US by
selling bottled drinks that appeal to an increasingly health-conscious
public. Annual sales shot up to Dollars 516m last year from Dollars 44m in
1990. Recently, however, Snapple's profits and share price have been hit by
the cost of geographical expansion and by competition from companies such as
Coca-Cola and Pepsi-Cola, which have jumped on to the alternative beverage
bandwagon. Snapple said net profits had sunk from Dollars 26.9m to Dollars
7.1m in the quarter to September.
Chicago-based Quaker Oats, for many months the subject of bid speculation,
has been under pressure to realign its businesses because of lacklustre
financial performance. Last week it reported a fall in net income from
Dollars 91.4m to Dollars 57.3m in the quarter to September, blaming weakness
in European petfood sales and increased marketing costs, especially for its
Gatorade sports drinks in North America.
Mr William Smithburg, Quaker chairman and chief executive, said the
combination of Gatorade and Snapple would create North America's largest
'good-for-you' beverage company, with market leadership in teas, juice
drinks and sports drinks.
He said the petfood and chocolate disposals would concentrate Quaker on
faster-growing, higher-margin businesses. The European petfoods business has
annual revenues of about Dollars 800m and Mexican chocolate has annual
revenues of about Dollars 100m. Mr Les Pugh, an analyst at Salomon Brothers,
the Wall Street investment bank, said the two would probably fetch about
Dollars 700m. He cited Nestle, the biggest European food company, as a
possible buyer.
