<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Base rate rise 'on hold' after monetary meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK bank base rates appeared last night to be on hold for this month after
yesterday's monthly monetary meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England.
But higher interest rates in the months ahead remained a possibility after
both men, in public comments before and after their 45-minute discussion,
emphasised their commitment to low inflation as the best way to promote UK
economic growth, competitiveness and job creation.
Mr Clarke, in an interview with BBC radio's Today programme, made clear
early yesterday that he and Mr George were at one in wanting underlying
inflation, which excludes mortgage interest rates below 2.5 per cent by the
end of this parliament.
Mr George, giving a lecture on unemployment last night, told a City audience
that 'timely - and in the end, smaller - increases in interest rates' were
less likely to damage investment and industrial confidence than inflation.
Neither the bank nor the Treasury would comment on the meeting. However, it
is believed that Mr George did not press for an increase in interest rates
this month. As the governor has been more insistent than the chancellor on
the need for timely interest rate increases in recent months, it was assumed
that yesterday's meeting decided to keep base rates at 5.75 per cent.
The bank this week indicated that base rates would probably have to rise
over the coming months. It detected a generally improved inflation outlook
over the next two years, but warned of the danger of stronger price
pressures. Nevertheless, its quarterly inflation report, published on
Tuesday, shied away from advocating an immediate rate rise. Instead it
concluded: 'It will be necessary to monitor these developments very
carefully.'
The Treasury's monthly monetary report, prepared for yesterday's meeting,
listed the economic factors that might argue for or against a tightening of
monetary policy. They remain finely balanced.
The Treasury said underlying inflation fell to a new 27-year low in
September. However, it added that monthly indicators of economic activity
'supported a picture of broadly based growth'.
Mr Clarke made clear that he and the bank agreed on the need for low
inflation. 'I am as keen on it as the governor of the Bank of England,' said
Mr Clarke, referring to the government's target of having inflation in the
bottom half of its 1-4 per cent range by the end of this parliament.
Economists rap Bank, Page 8
Samuel Brittan, Page 22
</TEXT>
