<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If his previous work is an accurate guide, Steve Humphries' documentary
series Forbidden Britain will be well worth watching. It looks at 'Britain's
secret past from 1900 to 1960' starting with juvenile crime (9.45 BBC2).
Remember the famous Channel 4 'remit'? Something to do with being different
and catering for minorities, wasn't it? Today they begin a series called
Beat That Einstein in which people with little scientific knowledge are
required to complete a task with the help of only a few books and garden
shed tools (8.00). Reminds you of 'The Great Egg Race'? Me too. Drop The
Dead Donkey is not dramatically different from other comedies, but it is
welcome since it is often funny (10.00). The programme that best exemplifies
the Channel 4 idea is Pagliacci which is transmitted at 2.45 in the morning.
This is not the British 1936 coloured film with Richard Tauber, but an even
more obscure offering: a monochrome 1947 version starring Tito Gobbi and
featuring Gina Lollobrigida in her first movie. She mimes the role of Nedda
which is sung by Onelia Fineschi. Set the VCR.
