<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / MPs step up calls over child agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pressure on the government to reform the controversial Child Support Agency
increased yesterday with demands for change from MPs.
Members of the Commons social security committee were, however, divided over
how far the changes should go, and its recommendations came in for immediate
criticism.
The agency was set up to ensure that absent parents, usually fathers, make
proper financial support for their children. It was bitterly attacked during
its first year of operation for making unrealistic financial demands, and
for the poor quality of its administration. Ms Ros Hepplewhite, chief
executive, resigned in September.
The committee calls in its report for special treatment for couples who
split up before the agency was established, reponding to complaints that it
had interfered with 'clean-break' settlements. The committee recommends
changes in the way earnings and maintenance are calculated, and improved
social security safety-net arrangements for single parents.
Although the committee's final report was unanimous, Conservative members
had earlier rejected proposals for further change, including an independent
appeals system and more beneficial financial arrangements for single and
absent parents.
The government is expected to revise the maintenance formula used by the
agency, but is unlikely to want to embark on the committee's wider programme
for change.
Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the committee, emphasised that it
remained united in the view that establishing the agency, 'revolutionary as
it is', was right in principle. However, Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social
security secretary, said the report would be 'condemned as tinkering with
the problem'.
</TEXT>
