<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / New form for assessing tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A tax form designed to help 9m people assess their payments is launched
today in draft form by the Inland Revenue.
The form is a crucial part of the government's plan to shift to
self-assessment - the biggest change in tax collection since the
introduction of PAYE half a century ago.
A thousand volunteers will receive the new form and have a month to complete
and return it to the 30 tax offices taking part in the study.
The form incorporates one radical departure. Instead of all taxpayers
getting the same bulky form, each will be targeted with specific returns
tailored to their tax history.
Self-assessment starts in 1997 and will mean that those currently sending in
tax forms, either personally or through agents, will be able to use the new
form.
It will involve the self-employed, business partners, company directors and
some employees and pensioners. It will not affect the 20m taxpayers who use
PAYE.
Initial research showed that people did not like elaborate forms which often
contained irrelevant sections. They also completed the form in two sessions.
First they found out what information was needed. Then they completed the
form.
As a result the new form has a guide which should meet the needs of
taxpayers trying to assess what they need to know and what they need to
complete.
A market research programme of interviews will be undertaken with those
taking part in the scheme.
</TEXT>
