<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Adverts called for on BBC2
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2 should be allowed to accept advertising and sponsorship, the
Incorporated Society of British Advertisers said yesterday in response to
the government's white paper on the future of the BBC.
A mixture of funding from the licence fee and advertisers would enable the
corporation to compete effectively with growing satellite and multimedia
rivals, said the society, which represents many of the UK's largest
advertisers.
Mr Kenneth Miles, the society's director-general, said all other 'leading
countries in Europe now have mixed funding for state channels, with
advertising as a major source of income'.
The society wants to see BBC1 continue to be funded through the licence fee,
while BBC2 would operate with advertising and sponsorship. The white paper,
published in July, reinforced the current universal licence fee arrangements
until at least 2001.
Separately, the Institute of Practitioners in Advertising, accused the BBC
of mirroring the commercial sector in its programming. It added: 'Why should
licence payers be obliged to fund programmes that would, in the absence of
the BBC, be provided by commercial broadcasters?'
