<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Shephard orders overhaul of careers advice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government curriculum advisers have been asked to overhaul careers advice in
secondary education, Mrs Gillian Shephard, the education secretary,
announced yesterday.
Her move is part of a package of measures, launched jointly with the
employment secretary, Mr Michael Portillo, to improve careers advice.
She said there would be more funding for training careers teachers -
although she could not give an amount before the Budget - and schools would
be required to plan careers policy jointly with local employers and careers
services.
Ministers have rejected proposals by employers' organisations to introduce
vouchers for careers guidance.
Mrs Shephard said she had asked Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of the School
Curriculum and Assessment Authority, to produce new guidelines for careers
guidance in secondary education.
She said that 'young people from the age of 11 do need to understand that
they are aiming for the world of work'.
Careers services, which are directly funded by the Department of Employment,
claimed that schools were not providing impartial advice but they were
influenced by funding incentives to recruit students to A-level courses,
rather than sending them to do vocational courses with further education
colleges, which compete with them for funds.
Mr Mike Eastwood, from the UK Heads of Career Services Association, claimed
there was 'evidence that some head teachers, because of the amount of money
flowing from having a young person in their sixth form, are very loath to
have unbiased guidance from school careers service officers'.
This follows last month's report by Ofsted, the schools watchdog, and by the
Further Education Funding Council for England, which said too many
sixth-formers were attempting inappropriate academic A-level courses, and
should be encouraged to take vocational qualifications instead.
Mr David Blunkett, the shadow education secretary, said that careers advice
was being hampered by the government's 'market dogma'. He added:
'Commercialising careers services has brought uncertainty and confusion to
an area in which quality and consistency of advice are essential.'
But Mr Tony Webb, the Confederation of British Industry's education
director, said he was pleased with the package.
He added that the partnership approach was realistic, given that there were
not yet enough providers of careers advice for a fully competitive market.
</TEXT>
