<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / BAT warns of challenge over pension liability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAT Industries, which owns insurers Allied Dunbar and Eagle Star, yesterday
said it might issue a legal challenge to regulators' plans for paying
compensation to people who followed poor advice to take a personal pension.
Mr Martin Broughton, group chief executive, said BAT believed that life
companies operating through direct sales forces - as Allied Dunbar largely
does - should not have any compensation liability for investors who have
been wrongly advised by independent financial advisers which then go out of
business.
The Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulator, last week
published a report on identifying and compensating people who had been
wrongly sold personal pensions.
It said that life companies and advisers should review at least 350,000
cases within the next two years. Some estimates put the bill at up to Pounds
2bn.
SIB did not say how the retail financial services sector should divide the
cost of compensating the victims of independent advisers which are unable to
meet their liabilities, and life companies are arguing fiercely about how
the expense should be split.
Mr Broughton said: 'We might finish up taking the SIB or somebody to court
if direct sellers were asked to pick up some of the spread of liabilities
for independent advisers. We would take every step to avoid that.'
SIB is already discussing a narrower point with Sun Life, another life
insurer. Sun Life, which does 90 per cent of its business through
independent advisers, says legal advice casts doubts on whether it will have
to contribute compensation in respect of independent advisers which have
already gone out of business.
Mr Les Owen, Sun Life chief general manager, said the insurer was also
taking legal advice about the duties of the trustees of occupational pension
schemes.
Mr Broughton emphasised that Allied Dunbar and Eagle Star would provide
compensation where they had mis-sold pensions.
He estimated the administrative cost to the two companies of identifying
potential victims as between Pounds 5m and Pounds 6m over the next two
years.
Lex, Page 24
BAT rises 21%, Page 25
