<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Solvency rules set to be diluted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is planning to make significant concessions to employers in
its pension reform legislation by watering down solvency requirements that
could have forced schemes to sell shares and buy UK government securities.
It is understood that a reference to the legislation will be contained in
the Queen's Speech later this month and that a bill will be presented in the
second week of December.
In a white paper issued in June, it was proposed that each occupational
pension scheme hold enough assets to be able to provide members with the
'cash equivalent' of their accrued pension entitlements. The amount of cash
needed to provide future benefits is dependent upon the rate of interest
earned in the years before retirement. Actuaries use returns on gilts as the
basis for such calculations because, unlike equity investments, the return
on a particular gilt can be calculated with some certainty over time.
Employers, who on average hold 80 per cent of their portfolios in UK and
international equities, feared the white paper proposals would involve their
schemes switching from equities into gilts. They could also involve making
significant cash injections into the schemes.
The government now intends to allow returns on equities to be used for
calculating cash equivalents for people within 10 years of their retirement
date. Only holdings of UK equities will count for this purpose.
A source familiar with the proposals said yesterday that although the
changes represented current government thinking, they had not yet been
etched in stone.
The government also intends that returns on equities be used to calculate
the value of assets needed to pay cash equivalents to existing pensioners.
</TEXT>
