<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Which? hits at high bank charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
High street banks and the Consumers' Association have clashed over the
latest Which? survey on the cost of borrowing, Alison Smith writes.
The association says that a combination of charges on unauthorised
overdrafts and interest levied on such accounts for even short periods can
be equivalent to millions of per cent if translated to an annualised
percentage rate basis.
It argues that the high levels of interim profits reported by the banks
intensifies the argument that they should cut their charges. It says there
are sharp differences in the range of charges imposed by banks and building
societies that offer current accounts, and urges customers facing high
charges to move.
The British Bankers' Association said the banks' interim results showed that
providing banking services for personal customers was 'one of the most
unprofitable activities which banks undertake'. It emphasised that more than
three quarters of personal customers do not pay charges.
