<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Probe finds flaws in sixth of insurers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Around one in six life insurance companies still showed serious weaknesses
and flaws in the second round of routine inspection visits by financial
watchdogs, the annual report by Lautro on the sector's regulation says.
The report, published today, describes the result as a 'disappointment'
although it notes that the position has improved since the earlier round of
inspections when a third of life insurers failed regulators' scrutiny.
Record fines of Pounds 300,000 were imposed earlier this year on Norwich
Union and on Premium Life, and the life industry has been warned for several
months that continuing failures would be severely penalised.
The report from Lautro, which has now been succeeded as life insurance
regulator by the Personal Investment Authority (PIA), shows the extent of
contraction in the life insurance sector, with the number of sales agents
acting directly for life companies dropping by more than a third to below
94,000 at the end of June. In July 1991 it was more than twice that number.
The document admits that plans for inspections were disrupted considerably
for nine weeks in the spring by the setting up of the PIA. This involved
training monitoring staff and then working on the process of approving
organisations for acceptance by the new regulator.
Lautro says there have been some signs of improvement in standards, citing
the shift in the causes of disciplinary action away from harm inflicted on
investors towards the risk of harm, and the fact that the number of
investigations was only about half that of the previous 12 months.
It notes, however, that there has been an increase in the number of
complaints - to 7,143 from 5,775 in the period covered by last year's
report.
</TEXT>
