<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Battle fought from behind enemy lines: A look at the union
campaign against privatising the Post Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the UCW postal workers' union, and his
senior colleagues are keen to avoid celebrating over the government's
disarray on privatising the Post Office.
But sitting round the table at the union's London headquarters yesterday,
with their advisers from consultants Lowe Bell, they were looking back with
satisfaction on the most effective and professional campaign by a British
union for a long time.
'We could have followed the traditional way of opposition - handing out
leaflets, holding protest meetings, going on marches, threatening strikes
and setting up a sub-committee of the committed. It would have been amateur
hour,' Mr Johnson said.
The union dispatched stickers, leaflets, balloons and cards as well as
handing in a petition to Downing Street with 1.75m signatures but recognised
this would not be enough.
'We were determined to win, not organise a glorious defeat,' Mr Johnson
said. This meant running a focused, professional campaign not simply to
mobilise public opinion but to win over the Conservative heartland and so
deprive the government of its slender parliamentary majority. 'We had to
cross political frontiers and get behind the enemy lines.'
Over the past four months this meant hiring Lowe Bell Political, an arm of
the consultants linked closely in the past with the Conservative party
machine. Mr Johnson said: 'Working with Lowe Bell has enabled us to get to
people we would otherwise would not have been able to do.' It even enabled
the union to penetrate Conservative Central Office to take part in a meeting
of the Conservative Political Centre.
But Lowe Bell's role should not be exaggerated. The union started its
anti-privatisation campaign in July 1992 when Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary, first decided to review the ownership of the Post
Office.
Mr Daniel Harris, communications officer, said: 'Public opinion has been
against Post Office privatisation from the start. We harnessed an existing
sympathetic mood.'
Ms Julia Simpson, head of communications, said: 'We have a positive message:
to see the highly profitable and popular Post Office stay in the public
sector but with new commercial freedom.'
The union campaign also set the pace with the help of discontented Post
Office managers who have fed the union with a series of embarrassing
internal documents to put Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, on
the defensive.
The union was kept informed by its contacts over the progress of the
privatisation plans inside the cabinet committee.
In May it was able to exploit knowledge of government hesitations to press
the case for a consultative rather than a white paper on the issue.
The first taste of success came when union leaders learnt that Mr John
Major, the prime minister, had insisted that the union's policy option for
the Post Office should be included in Mr Heseltine's green paper.
The union has also widened its campaign by forming alliances with Women's
Institutes and campaigners for the preservation of rural England. And the
union's members, with their unique access to the public, were vital to the
campaign.
The champagne may still be on ice at union headquarters but it believes the
government's problems are due to its own efforts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
