<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Political Notebook: The surreal world of Major's enemy
within
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So now we know. It is all Mr John Major's fault. Everything. 'Sleaze',
ministerial sojourns at the Ritz, high taxes, rising crime rates, Sir Leon
Brittan's demotion, confusion over the Post Office, the chaos at the Child
Support Agency. That of course is a severely abridged list.
How can we be so sure that the prime minister alone must shoulder the blame?
Easy. Just spend a few minutes in the lobbies and bars of the House of
Commons. It is there, not on the opposition benches of the Commons chamber,
that Mr Major's real enemies still gather.
They sit on the government back benches. They call themselves the Tory
right. They are available any day, any hour: ready to whisper with
ill-concealed glee and synthetic resignation how once again Mr Major has
made a hash of it.
The issue that originally brought them together - Europe - has temporarily
slipped down the agenda during the pause between Maastricht and the 1996
intergovernmental conference. But it will return. And the bile and
bitterness remain.
The raison d'etre of these self-styled guardians of the Thatcherite flame is
simple: to denigrate the prime minister. They never miss a chance.
In this surreal world the abrupt return to their ranks of the sacked
industry minister Mr Neil Hamilton is almost a cause for celebration. Mr
Hamilton may be a fellow-traveller in trouble. But the manner of his
departure hands them yet another stick with which to beat Mr Major. And now,
of course, Mr Hamilton is free to say what he really thinks of the prime
minister in whose government he served.
The two dozen Tory MPs who peddle the poison in the Commons corridors of
course are only a fragment of what was once recognisable as the party's
right wing. The battle over Maastricht provided the illusion of a coherent
power bloc. But in reality the Tory right has fractured and divided since
the departure of Baroness Thatcher.
Its thinkers - Mr Michael Portillo, Mr Peter Lilley, Mr John Redwood and Mr
Michael Forsyth - are in government, bound - if sometimes only loosely - by
the gag of collective responsibility. The heavyweights of the 1980s have
retired hurt to the House of Lords. With the honourable exception of
intellectuals such as Mr John Biffen and clever mavericks such as Mr
Nicholas Budgen, that leaves little firepower on the back benches.
Take the most bitter malcontents. One or two have influence among less
committed colleagues. A few of the younger ones can look forward one day to
a career in government - maybe. But the rest are never-has-beens or
never-will-be's, the flotsam and jetsam of a party in power for 16 years.
Sir George Gardiner, Mr John Townend, Mr John Carlisle and the like profess
to worship the memory of Lady Thatcher. But she would not have them in her
administrations. Nor will any other Tory prime minister, left, right or
centre.
Now, their views - crudely populist as well as intellectually inconsistent -
are treated with mild embarrassment by their mentors in Mr Major's cabinet.
Sir George wants income tax cuts now and billions slashed at a stroke from
the welfare budget. Mr Portillo, his idol, dismisses as absurd the notion
that a Conservative government could cut taxes while it is borrowing Pounds
30bn a year. Meanwhile, he is busy defending his employment budget from the
Treasury axe.
Messrs Portillo, Lilley, and Redwood are no friends of the prime minister,
and regard him as weak. They nurture the power base on the back benches
which prevents him from sacking any of them.
But they are interested in winning the intellectual argument, not in
sticking pins into Mr Major or in seeing him replaced in 10 Downing Street
by Mr Kenneth Clarke.
Among the younger irreconcilables - the self-styled Essex right of the 1992
intake - there are a handful interested in argument as well as sniping.
Mr Iain Duncan-Smith is respected by those who mix in the same circles. Mr
John Whittingdale speaks with the experience of several years as a close
assistant to Lady Thatcher.
But by and large the young malcontents are sure of little else but their
dislike of Mr Major and a hatred of Brussels. Britain can and should be
great again. But it is not their role to explain how.
Therein lies the danger for Mr Major. His enemies are not susceptible to
rational argument. They are not interested in the politics of pragmatism
required to hold the Tory coalition together.
They have no credible alternative, but they would delight in the destruction
of the prime minister. They expect the forthcoming battle over Europe to
provide the opportunity, by widening the net of discontent on the back
benches and rebuilding the illusion of unity and intellectual coherence on
the right. But watch out Mr Major - any excuse will do.
</TEXT>
