<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Blair to review voluntary sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair last night ordered a thorough review of Labour's policies on
the voluntary sector, saying he wanted to propose 'a new deal' between
voluntary organisations and the government.
The Labour leader called for a middle path between the left's old belief in
state intervention and the right's view that voluntary bodies relieved the
government of its own responsibilities. Labour had learnt from the mistakes
of the past. 'The state does not have the solution to every problem. Nor do
people want the state to intervene in all areas of life,' he said.
Offering one or two hints as to what the conclusions of the review might be,
Mr Blair said the proposed new deal must be based on a recognition that the
voluntary sector was not a 'cut-price alternative to statutory provision'.
'Why should the state provide all the training for the unemployed when
voluntary organisations in many cases are providing innovative schemes,' he
said.
The review is to be conducted by Mr Alun Michael, the shadow home affairs
minister, a staunch Blair loyalist.
</TEXT>
