</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GCHQ, the government's secret communications centre at Cheltenham, yesterday
announced it would shed 300 to 500 jobs over the next three years.
The centre, which employs about 6,000 people, said it hoped to achieve most
of the job losses through non-replacement and voluntary redundancies. Two
hundred jobs have already gone over the past two years.
GCHQ blamed the cuts on a 'tightening of the purse strings' throughout the
Civil Service. It added: 'Money is tight and there are restrictions on
public expenditure.' The ending of the Cold War was also to blame.
An official of the GCHQ staff federation said: 'Morale has steadily fallen
over the last few years and I am sure there will be no shortage of
volunteers for redundancy.' The federation replaced unions following the
controversial ban on them by the government 10 years ago,
