<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / M&amp;G raises fears over market plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
M&amp;G, the independent unit trust company, says the London Stock Exchange's
proposed Alternative Investment Market will not be suitable for the
investors who buy its retail products because of the low level of regulation
and disclosure.
M&amp;G is one of several leading managers of unit trusts which have expressed
concern over the proposed market, which is intended to replace the Unlisted
Securities Market at the end of 1996. M&amp;G's objections are significant
because it has developed expertise in small-company share investment.
Mr Jonathan Bartlett, who manages M&amp;G's smaller companies unit trust, said:
'We don't believe it is right for unit trust holders to invest in these kind
of stocks. There may be investors there but they won't be M&amp;G unit holders.'
Professional groups of institutional investors, including the Association of
British Insurers, have told the Stock Exchange of their concerns that the
proposals offer too little investor protection to encourage significant
investment in the smallest companies.
However, small companies have been urging the exchange to devise a mechanism
to replace the USM which will help them raise capital at a lower cost than
seeking a place on the exchange's official list.
</TEXT>
