<TEXT>
Indonesian authorities are cracking down on government critics, labour
activists and alleged criminals to 'clean up' the capital Jakarta before
next week's Asia Pacific Economic Co-operation summit, according to Amnesty
International, the London-based human rights organisation. It said yesterday
the crackdown began with an anti-crime campaign in April but had been
broadened to include 'arbitrary arrest of political detainees, some of whom
had been tortured and ill-treated, the unfair trial and arbitrary
imprisonment of labour activists and the dramatic escalation in the number
of unlawful killings of alleged criminals.'
