<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Standard Chartered fined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Standard Chartered Securities, the stockbroking arm of Standard Chartered
Bank, has been fined HKDollars 500,000 by the Hong Kong stock exchange and
publicly censured for stock manipulation and 'rat-trading' activities -
whereby trades for customers are booked through an employee's private
accounts with other stockbrokers to the detriment of the client and
advantage of the broker. The exchange's disciplinary committee found
Standard Chartered Securities failed to exercise proper supervision of its
employees between July 1991 and March 1993, which led to the company
breaking several rules.
