</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
At least 13 people, including the commander of the Algiers military
district, died in a shoot-out yesterday that ended a 24-hour standoff
between police and Moslem militants in the Algerian capital. The clash was
the bloodiest single gun battle in the capital during the 33-month conflict
pitting Islamic extremists against the military-backed regime. Among the
dead was Col Cherif Djelloul, shot by gunmen as he tried to negotiate the
release of hostages. The government, meanwhile, returned two fundamentalist
leaders to jail after they urged militants to continue their rebellion,
which has left more than 11,000 dead.
