<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / India sees spurt in investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India saw a sharp rise in foreign investment inflows in the five months to
August, the finance ministry said yesterday. It estimated the inflow reached
Dollars 2.1bn (Pounds 1.4bn), compared with Dollars 4.1bn in the financial
year 1993-94. Direct investment rose to Dollars 381m in the five months,
against Dollars 620m for 1993-94. Ministry officials said total foreign
investment in 1994-95 might surpass last year's levels. The figures do not
yet include any significant contributions from planned large-scale projects
in power generation and oil refining which could start producing investment
inflows in the next 12 months.
'The surge in foreign investment in recent times is one of the direct
manifestations of the success of the economic reforms,' the ministry said in
a mid-year review of the economy. The report paints a positive picture of
the economic outlook, saying growth in 1994-95 is likely to exceed 5 per
cent, 'much higher' than last year's 3.8 per cent. Agricultural output is
good, industrial production is recovering, inflation is being controlled and
exports continue to grow, though more slowly than last year.
</TEXT>
