FT  03 NOV 94 / Strikes ground Iberia flights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iberia, Spain's financially crippled state airline, has been forced to
ground most of its flights today as unions stage the first of two 24-hour
strikes this month. The unions are objecting to the company's refusal to
make up back pay that was due at the end of October and to its plans to
reduce salaries by an average of 15 per cent over the next two years. The
airline cancelled all its international flights serving routes that are
covered by other airlines, as well as 70 per cent of its domestic flights.
Iberia is on course to lose Pta44bn (Pounds 216m) this year. The industrial
dispute could delay its efforts to gain European Union authorisation for
fresh public funding of at least Pta125bn. Unions say Pta200bn will be
required to assure future viability. A second strike is planned on November
11.
