<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Croatian Serbs mass for fight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SARAJEVO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serbs facing a joint Moslem-Croat assault have enlisted the help of
rebel Serb guns in neighbouring Croatia to fight a offensive by the Bosnian
government army, United Nations officers said yesterday. Croatian Serbs were
reported to have mobilised 2,000 troops and to have massed men and weaponry
along the border, although there was no evidence that they had crossed it.
Intense fighting was reported in the suburbs of Serb-held Bosanska Krupa in
northwest Bosnia, but Serb fighters were holding off the attack.
The Bosnian government troops' advance out of the Bihac northwestern enclave
has slowed after a week-long offensive that pushed Serb soldiers from almost
100 square miles of conquered territory. UN observers were barred from most
of the battle zone, and each side was claiming the upper hand.
According to a UN officer, Bosnian Serbs also faced fresh attacks near
Sarajevo and Bosnian Croat forces joined the Moslem offensive in central
Bosnia in a joint action on the Serb-held town of Kupres. Significant Croat
troop movements were reported in the area.
