<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 94 / Russian cabinet shake-up looms: Changes in economics and
justice portfolios under discussion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A shake-up in the Russian cabinet was on the cards last night. Mr Ivan
Rybkin, chairman of the state duma (lower house), said following a meeting
with President Boris Yeltsin that a reshuffle would take place within one or
two weeks.
A spokesman for Mr Rybkin said after the meeting that the posts discussed
included those of the economics and justice minister and 'a range of changes
among the deputy prime ministers'. The economics portfolio is held by Mr
Alexander Shokhin, a reformer who is now thought to be vulnerable but may
retain his parallel post as deputy prime minister.
The Itar-Tass news agency said the discussion took place in the context of a
state duma vote of no-confidence in the government which failed by only 30
votes. Only 54 deputies from 450 actively voted for the government.
It also comes after a Moscow by-election last weekend which was won by the
candidate backed by the ultra-nationalist Liberal Democratic party, and
local elections in St Petersburg which saw a strong showing for the
communists.
Neither the nationalist nor the communist parties have any representative in
the cabinet.
The discussion between the duma chairman and Mr Yeltsin came after details
emerged of the report on 'black Tuesday' by the Security Council commission,
which is staffed wholly by military and security chiefs. On that day,
October 11, the rouble plunged to Rbs4,000 to the dollar. It later recovered
to around Rbs2,800 but has since declined again, if gently, to Rbs3,093.
According to the presidential press service, the report accused a number of
senior public servants of 'ill-timed, if not incompetent, decisions' and
said that there was 'insufficient co-ordination between the federal bodies
of the executive branch'. It ordered the government to take immediate
control of the currency exchange rate and 'consolidate the legal backbone of
the financial, including the currency, market'.
The Interfax news agency, quoting 'well-informed sources', said that the
Council's report named the economics and finance ministries, the central
bank and several commercial banks as having 'profited directly and
considerably from destabilising the national financial system'.
The acting finance minister and the governor of the central bank both
resigned after the collapse of the currency last month.
The report says, according to Interfax's sources, that the collapse will
'entail long term and deep negative consequences for the Russian economy'
because foreign investors 'now doubt the expediency of investing in Russia'.
It recommended continuing investigation and, if necessary, criminal
proceedings.
Mr Rybkin, an increasingly authoritative figure, said that the sackings of
the central bank governor and finance minister would be followed by
'bringing to book some of their deputies'. On Mr Shokhin's fate, he
commented ominously that 'it will be decided by the government'.
In discussions on the passage of the budget through the parliament, Mr
Rybkin said that Mr Yeltsin had described as 'unconstitutional' the legal
provision under which the government had to resign if the budget fell, and
had called for the Constitutional Court, now being recreated after a year's
non-existence, to look into the issue. The discussion appears to point to
fears that the budget will not pass.
Rumours abound about who would replace Mr Shokhin, but none point to his
successor being a reformist figure. Since his removal would come following a
report drawn up by representatives of the security services and the
military, it is widely assumed that a more conservative figure would emerge
 -with others of the same stripe possibly also taking their place in the
cabinet.
The discussion was remarkable for the absence of Mr Victor Chernomyrdin who,
as prime minister, would be expected to command a cabinet apparently chosen
by the president and the duma chairman.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
