<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (21): Nightmare at a top
American school - The first three terms are portrayed with wit and
self-deprecation as a gruesome mental assault course / Business education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'SNAPSHOTS FROM HELL (THE MAKING OF AN MBA)' By Peter Robinson Nicholas
Brealey Pounds 9.99, 286 pages
Perhaps the most surprising thing about Peter Robinson's book is that it is
actually a rather entertaining read. One could imagine lots of MBA students
recounting the experiences of their first year at business school and the
results being decidedly dull.
Robinson, however, enjoys a number of advantages. For a start, he can write,
a skill no doubt developed in his earlier White House job drafting speeches
for President Reagan. He also describes an interesting business school era
(1988-90), when the yuppie union card, as he calls the MBA, was already
starting to lose some of its shine, as well as an interesting institution
(Stanford University Graduate School of Business) which, by his account,
appears to have been in some turmoil at the time.
Above all, however, Robinson is a sufficiently sympathetic and sensitive
character for readers to want to know whether he survived his nightmare, how
it changed him and what judgments on business education he ultimately made.
Many of Robinson's difficulties arise from the fact that he is a 'poet'  -
Stanford-speak for students with degrees in subjects such as history or
English as opposed to engineering or mathematics, and who instinctively
prefer ideas rather than numbers. Large parts of the more
mathematically-based bits of the syllabus are therefore at best baffling, at
worst likely to make him 'flunk' the whole programme.
He has periods of relaxation, elation and joy but on the whole the first
three terms of a full-time MBA at one of America's top schools are portrayed
with wit and self-deprecation as a gruesome mental assault course - at least
for poets, that is.
There is some interest in the other characters - Conor, a fellow poet with
spouse and family in tow, struggling with 27-hour days; Zen, a Japanese who
finally cannot bring himself to make the cultural leap and work for a US
firm; and Mr Cool and Mr Perfect who, as their nicknames imply, found it all
easy enough to womanise and improve their suntans. Generally, though,
Robinson's classmates are types one might recognise anywhere.
What is more provoking is the light this book sheds on the value of an MBA.
Things have moved on on both sides of the Atlantic since the author's
graduation - a pity, in fact, that he wasn't a bit quicker on the draw with
his pen - but the observations are still instructive for anyone
contemplating business school today.
Even a school with Stanford's reputation is sometimes guilty in Robinson's
view of sloppy and ill-focused teaching (the class is in open revolt at one
point), close friendships are hard to forge, especially in the early
pressure-cooker days, and the networking-job-seeking mentality is even more
obsessive than one imagines.
Robinson cites an iconoclastic member of the faculty who dreams of running
two MBA classes side by side: one would follow the normal curriculum, the
other would do no work and spend the time playing golf or on the beach. His
point is that given many employers' starry-eyed attitude to the MBA, the
more leisurely lot would be just as successful in the job market as the
'genuine' students.
Robinson's own search to some extent proves the point - an offer from Robert
Maxwell during a meeting in which he literally did not have to open his
mouth. Wisely, he turned that one down, although the subsequent decision to
accept Rupert Murdoch's shilling was scarcely more auspicious. Robinson
later fell victim to a cost-cutting programme implemented by the Australian
tycoon.
Based on the class of 1988-90 as a whole, the conclusion is that business
school is not necessarily a straight and easy road to riches. But in the
end, Robinson betrays an affectionate regard for the institution which put
him through hell: he says the union card, the broadening experience, the
self-confidence, the contacts and (in his case, at any rate) the perspective
on life, are all worth having.
A case, perhaps, of not biting too hard the hand that feeds you.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
