<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (22): 'Winners and losers'
theory - Whatever their rhetoric, most western governments have all but
abandoned a practical commitment to full employment / Macroeconomics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUW DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THE GOALS OF MACROECONOMIC POLICY' By Martin Prachowny Routledge, Pounds
13.99, 217 pages
Martin Prachowny's book has as its central theme the observation that
macroeconomic policies generate winners and losers: there is always a
conflict of interest, and policies that make everyone better off do not
exist.
The most important conflict that Prachowny identifies is between two groups
of workers: on one hand those in secure jobs, on the other those in
relatively insecure jobs and the unemployed.
In a democratic system, the conduct of policy is decided by the 'median
voter', Mr/Ms Average, who belong to the 'secure' group. This group is
unlikely to lose their job except under extreme circumstances, and are
relatively unenthusiastic about funding expansionary government programmes
for reducing unemployment.
Those not in secure jobs form a minority, and hence the democratic system
does not deliver policies which would benefit them.
This observation certainly has a ring of truth about it for those who
witnessed the surprise victory of the Conservative party in the UK under
John Major in 1991. Whatever their rhetoric, at the end of the day most
western governments have all but abandoned a practical commitment to full
employment.
There were two main pillars of 'Keynesian' policy for 25 years after the
second world war. First, a belief that 'full employment' was achievable, and
that it was desirable. Second, a belief that governments could stabilise the
economy around full employment by a 'countercyclical' demand management
policy (boosting demand in recessions, restraining it in booms).
Both of these pillars rested on the foundation that it was possible in the
context of a big depression to have an expansion of output and employment
that made everyone better off.
Government spending would take people out of unemployment, and they would
then consume goods, thus generating more employment and profits.
Prachowny denies this, believing that an increase in employment cannot
happen without a fall in real wages: an increase in employment which
benefits the unemployed leads to a fall in the wages of those in employment.
This notion has little empirical validity: indeed, most empirical analysis
shows that the real wages of workers rise in booms. The power of those in
employment to obtain higher wages is increased when unemployment is falling.
More importantly, Prachowny does not take into account the fact that
government spending is itself useful.
There is a growing body of research in the US and elsewhere that public
investment and education expenditure have a positive impact on productivity
in the private sector. Just think of the huge costs imposed on British
industry by the lack of an adequate transport infrastructure.
Taking these factors together might indicate that the winners might be more
numerous than Prachowny suggests.
There is a clear truth in some of what Prachowny says. However, this book
mentions neither poverty nor inequality. The years since 1980 have seen a
dramatic increase in both poverty and inequality in most western economies.
In European countries, the poverty is primarily related to unemployment: in
the US it is primarily due to low wages for the unskilled.
The real split is between the unskilled and the skilled. Job security is
part of this difference (although since the shakeout of middle management
and the financial sector, few jobs are secure in the old sense). The
unskilled are becoming redundant technologically, and are competing with
workers in China and eastern Europe. The relative wages of the unskilled are
falling, and are likely to continue falling. The wages of the skilled have
continued to rise. The unskilled are likely to endure more frequent or
prolonged unemployment.
The labour market is thus divided into two separate parts, which are driven
by different factors. The growing social and economic distance between the
skilled and the unskilled gives rise to the features that Prachowny
highlights. The key feature is that the wages of the skilled are not related
to those of the unskilled: but the taxes of the skilled are related to
government expenditure.
Those who benefit from relative private affluence rarely feel motivated to
pay taxes to fund public affluence. The key developments in the labour
market since 1980, and the politics of Thatcher and Reagan, are ignored by
Prachowny who emphasises the continuity of the problem facing politicians.
From an economist's perspective, this book is a strange brew. Most of the
parts are not strong: neither theory nor empirics. The historical policy
analysis of the US 1948-1990 is perhaps the most interesting chapter. At the
end of the book, one is not only left to wonder whether the book has missed
some of the most important developments: one is also left wondering whether
the parts form a consistent whole. While the book provides interesting
insights and a romp through several ideas, it should not be taken with much
more than a pinch of salt.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
