<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (17): Lessons for today -
Labour's beacon of hope would seem to have all the promise of a Cornish
wrecker's lantern / Unemployment policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'IDLE HANDS, THE EXPERIENCE OF UNEMPLOYMENT, 1790 TO 1990' By John Burnett
Routledge, Pounds 14.99, 384 pages
If the Labour party insists on clinging to its goal of full employment when
it compiles its manifesto at the time of the next general election it will
inevitably fall back on a single historical example to convince a sceptical
electorate that it is anything more than a pipe dream.
The two golden decades of virtually full employment after the second world
war, are Labour's beacon of hope and, as such, would seem to have all the
promise of a Cornish wrecker's lantern. The period was exceptional,
historically atypical, and unlikely to be repeated, concludes John Burnett
in Idle Hands, a social history of unemployment in the 200 years up to 1990.
After reading this comprehensive and thoughtful work it is difficult to
disagree. Unlike the cyclical nature of many of the economic factors
associated with unemployment in much of this study, the problems of a
post-industrial economy, he argues, differ from those of the past when a
large manufacturing base survived through periods of depression.
That said, there are many lessons in this work of relevance to today, not
least his finding that reductions in unemployment relief as a deterrence in
response to a suspicion that the unemployed were workshy or scroungers, did
nothing to create jobs.
Burnett examines the underlying reasons for and conditions surrounding
unemployment. He focuses on the experience of the handloom weavers, a large
and successful semi-skilled elite of the 18th and early 19th century, and
considers their plight in the light of today's socio-economic conditions.
The handloom weavers enjoyed social prominence and comparative wealth among
the working classes for a brief period towards the end of the 18th century.
Developments in power-loom weaving emerged when the Napoleonic wars were
coming to an end. Thus, just as the working population swelled, the number
of available jobs was declining.
Ironically it was the very success and efficiency of handloom weaving,
speeded even further by the appearance of Kay's flying shuttle, that created
the incentive to mechanise spinning. This led to large supplies of cotton
yarn. Finding themselves in short supply, the handloom weavers briefly
prospered as technologies struggled with the more difficult task of
mechanising weaving.
The very developments that made weaving easier, however, also increased the
use of cheaper unskilled labour to fill demand. Jobs were taken by farm
labourers often working alongside women and children.
As the Napoleonic wars ended, releasing thousands of servicemen into an
already squeezed labour market, it seems hardly surprising that outbreaks of
farm machinery burning and Luddism became commonplace. Some 390 threshing
machines were smashed in 1830-31. Rioting was widespread. More than a
thousand rioters were convicted; half of them were imprisoned and half
transported - and 19 were hanged.
The period coincided with the new political philosophy of laisser faire.
There was to be no employment protection from parliament. As French
blockades cut down supplies of raw cotton during the war years, the
handlooming industry plunged into depression.
In the early days of Luddism, Burnett notes, power looms were still in their
infancy and he sees them more as a focus of discontent rather than its chief
cause. While Luddism itself was only part of a much broader unrest, it was
brought to prominence by the intensity of its violence associated with
attacks on mills. The weavers became the backbone of a politicised movement
that culminated in an armed rising in the West Riding and an attempt to
capture Huddersfield in 1820.
Further insurrection occurred in Scotland. Military intervention, arrests,
hangings and transportations were repeated in many industrial towns. As
depression spread some communities faced famine, Chartism began to flourish
as a quasi-revolutionary movement and mill attacks became more organised and
intensified across the Lancashire cotton belt and into the Yorkshire Wollen
mills.
The unrest precipitated the first large debate on the economic and social
consequences of technological change. The debate polarised on familiar
lines, one side arguing that mechanisation increased demand for labour and
was essential to remain competitive, the other side arguing, somewhat
nostalgically, that it would lead to the break-up of the family unit and
moral decline.
Unemployment today, writes Burnett somewhat bleakly, has become a continuing
feature of social and economic life. We cannot expect other sectors to
compensate for the dramatic decline in Britain's industrial base, he says.
The Labour party may yet be reminded of Sir Keith Joseph, the former
Conservative minister's words in 1978. He said: 'Full employment is not in
the gift of Government. It should not be promised and it cannot be
provided.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
