</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (16): Focus on profits curbed
reforms - The authors leave the NYSE with a stark choice: adapt or die / New
York Stock Exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'REVOLUTION ON WALL STREET: THE RISE AND DECLINE OF THE NEW YORK STOCK
EXCHANGE' by Marshall E Blume, Jeremy J Siegel and Dan Rottenberg Norton,
Pounds 19.95, 320 pages
The prologue to Revolution on Wall Street opens with an irresistible quote:
'You gentlemen are making a great mistake. The Exchange is a perfect
institution.'
So said stockbroker Richard Whitney in 1934. The then president of the NYSE,
Whitney was telling the US Senate of his opposition to plans to create the
Securities and Exchange Commission, a watchdog that would police the rapidly
expanding US financial markets. In spite of his confidence, Whitney fooled
no one. The SEC was duly set up, and four years later Whitney himself was
imprisoned for the theft of his client's securities.
In its 200 years, the NYSE has had its fair share of Richard Whitneys. Yet
Revolution on Wall Street does not dwell long on the crooks and con-men. The
book's main purpose is to tell the story of the NYSE, how the world's
greatest stock exchange ended up today as an impressive, still-powerful
institution, but one besieged by technological change and competitive forces
that threaten its very existence. It does this very well.
Although the narrative occasionally digresses into technical issues - such
as the collapse of the Bretton Woods exchange rate system; the development
of new investment theories and techniques by academics and professional
money managers; and the oil and inflation crises of the 1970s - the authors
(two University of Pennsylvania professors, Marshall Blume and Jeremy
Siegel, and financial journalist Dan Rottenberg) manage to keep their eyes
on the ball most of the time.
At each juncture in the story, they explain how exterior forces were
fashioning a new, less regulated, financial system, and how the NYSE stood
by while the financial world around it was reshaped.
In the 1970s, for example, the book tells how the birth of the financial
futures and options markets in Chicago left the New York markets, and the
NYSE in particular, trailing in the wake of innovation.
Within a few years, the enormous popularity of stock index futures such as
the future on the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 meant that share price levels were
increasingly being determined in the futures trading pits in Chicago, and
not in New York on the NYSE's floor - as investors would discover to their
cost in October, 1987.
The authors also tell, in brisk and readable fashion, of the rise of the
institutional investor - a new, smarter version than the NYSE had ever
encountered before - of their revolt against the fixed-commission system
that had for so long filled the pockets of the brokers with easy money, of
the breakdown of the securities clearing system, and of the arrival of the
first computers.
This is when the book's central theme - the Exchange's failure to adapt to
technological change - begins to emerge. In the 1970s, while the SEC was
promoting the establishment of an electronic system for centralising the
trading on all the nation's different exchanges and markets, and while small
regional exchanges and broking firms were using computer technology to
develop new methods of buying and selling securities that by-passed the
traditional trading floors, the NYSE was fiercely for the status quo.
By the 1980s, the new markets - such as the Nasdaq screen-based
'over-the-counter' trading system, and the 'third' and 'fourth' markets
where securities firms and institutions traded with each other or within
their own institutions - were flourishing, and the NYSE was losing market
share.
At this time, the NYSE was not entirely neglecting the new technology. It
invested millions in updating its trade processing, monitoring and
compliance systems. Yet, as the authors point out, the basic procedures for
trading securities at the Exchange hardly changed at all. Market-makers, or
'specialists', were still at their trading posts on the floor handling
transactions on behalf of brokers and their customers.
And while that system remained unchanged, investors, small and large, began
discovering other, newer systems which offered cheaper, more efficient
service - such as Bernard Madoff Securities' in-house market, which not only
offered to execute trades for no charge, but actually paid broking houses to
direct the flow of orders its way.
The reason why the NYSE has failed to adapt to change is simple, say the
authors: the Exchange is run by its members, the specialists and brokers,
whose overriding concern is their own profitability. The ancient structure
of the NYSE virtually guarantees that profitability - any reforms to alter
drastically the structure, would undermine it. Hence, the NYSE's resistance
to change.
The authors leave the NYSE with a stark choice: adapt or die. It should take
control of the Exchange away from the members, and start developing one or
more new trading systems to suit the needs of the investors, not the
intermediaries. Whether the NYSE's members will heed this advice is
doubtful.
</TEXT>
