<DATE>941102
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (14): A revisionist explanation
 -The British system is now similar, in scale if not yet in ethos, to that
in the rest of Europe and the US / Higher education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER SCOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'HIGHER EDUCATION AND CORPORATE REALITIES: CLASS, CULTURE AND THE DECLINE OF
GRADUATE CAREERS' by Phillip Brown and Richard Scase UCL Press, Pounds
12.95, 208 pages
Two grand phenomena are examined in this book.
The first has been grindingly reiterated for decades: the decline of big-bad
bureaucracies, whether in the public or private sectors, and the
corresponding rise of 'flexible' organisations, lean and loose-coupled with
flat hierarchies, all but their core activities contracted out or
cost-centred.
According to business gurus and social analysts, we are on the cusp of the
Fordist and post-Fordist ages.
The second, less widely rehearsed phenomenon, is the expansion of higher
education.
During the past 10 years, almost in a fit of absent-mindedness, Britain has
acquired a mass system. With a third of young people, and a growing number
of the not-so-young, going on to universities or colleges, the British
system is now similar, in scale if not yet in ethos, to higher education in
the rest of Europe and the US.
This book, written by two University of Kent sociologists, is an attempt to
relate these two trends.
They offer a revisionist, counter-intuitive explanation.
The standard account stresses cause and effect. Universities and other
higher education institutions have expanded to meet a growing need for
highly skilled labour and, through their research, help build a
technology-based economy.
This was true yesterday. The American land-grant universities - California,
Michigan, Wisconsin and the rest - were established to unlock the (largely
agricultural) wealth of the west in the post-Civil War decades, and our
civic universities founded in the nineteenth century grew, although
obliquely, out of the industrial revolution.
A generation ago, the link between the Robbins-induced expansion of the
universities and Harold Wilson's 'white heat of the technological
revolution' was taken for granted.
It is true today. Much of the recent expansion of students has been in
occupationally relevant subjects such as business studies and the 'softer'
sciences and technologies.
The title of this year's White Paper on science and technology was Realising
Our Potential, and an explicit reference to wealth-creation (along with
improving the quality of life) has been included in the missions of the
reorganised research councils.
It will be true tomorrow. Advanced economies are knowledge-based. Profits
are generated more by the application of ideas than the intensive
exploitation of raw materials or the increasing productivity of labour - or,
rather, the latter are dependent on the former.
In the post-industrial economy, wired into and up by the super-highways of
Information Technology, universities as leading components of the knowledge
industry are key players.
The authors offer a contrary interpretation. They cast doubt on these
supposedly symbiotic links between the development of advanced economies and
the growth of mass higher education systems. They argue that the latter is
far better explained in terms of the accumulation of cultural capital -
socio-economic status as embodied in intellectual manners and academic
qualifications - than of enhanced investment in human capital - the demand
for more sophisticated expert skills and the satisfaction of this demand.
Indeed, they push their revisionism two stages further. First, they argue
that universities, as organisations, and so the careers for which they
prepare their graduates, reflect the old world of planned bureaucracy, both
welfare state and industrial-age.
The professional society of which the former were agents and which was
reflected in the latter is being rapidly eroded.
Second, to the extent that a post-Fordist economy, and the 'flexible'
organisations that are its hallmark, value 'charismatic' and 'transferable'
skills more highly than bureaucratic and technical skills, the effect may be
a regression to older criteria for assessing the comparative worth of higher
education graduates. Self-confidence, 'character' may count for more than
either expertise or experience in the future.
Their conclusions are based on comparatively small-scale surveys of student
attitudes and employer expectations.
The students surveyed were at Oxbridge, a 'Home Counties' university and an
'Inner City' university. The empirical evidence produced by these surveys is
suggestive rather than conclusive, and predictable.
It is not difficult to elicit examples of juvenile arrogance from Oxbridge
students or envious under-confidence from their polytechnic peers. But
whether they can sustain weighty theorising is more doubtful.
Also, the thrust of their conclusions is unclear.
If universities must prepare graduates for 'flexible' careers, the more
enterprising institutions less burdened by donnish baggage should be at an
advantage.
But if new-style 'charisma' is going to be boiled down to old-fashioned
'character', the more traditional universities will benefit.
However, this intriguing book serves to emphasise two key points.
First, mass higher education is a social and cultural phenomenon, although
not perhaps a class phenomenon as the authors suggest.
Expansion has been the result of push from below, not pull from above. Its
primary imperative is the democratic not the skills revolution; its purpose,
more cynically, to preserve social order.
Second, in the (post-?)modern economy where production has yielded pride of
place to consumption and a truly global market has eroded national
differentiation, traditional assumptions about the tight, even causal,
association between modernity - secular, liberal, sceptical and free-market
values - and modernisation, the process of technology-driven wealth
creation, may need to be rethought.
This book is a valuable aid to such re-thinking. Modernity may no longer be
a necessary precondition of modernisation which would leave universities,
synthesisers of both, in an awkward corner.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
