<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (12): Big issue revisited - Can
Chicago's South Shore Bank experiment act as a model for inner-city
regeneration / Local investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRIAN WRIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'COMMUNITY CAPITALISM' By Richard P Taub Harvard Business School Press
Dollars 14.95, 151 pages
One of the more obscure economic indicators is the use of the work
'trickledown'. Beloved of those who believe in the regenerative powers of
large-scale projects - interestingly bridging Margaret Thatcher and Maynard
Keynes - trickledown is currently in hibernation and there is a touching
revival in community and local initiative. However the big issue in local
investment is just that; who invests and is it really investment or is it a
grant?
With the British Government preparing to back a trial local investment
scheme in two areas of the UK, the new edition of Richard Taub's Community
Capitalism is very timely. The book is a history of Chicago's South Shore
Bank and its strapline 'Strategy for Neighbourhood Revitalisation' sums up
the author's ambitions for its scope.
The South Shore Bank is often mentioned as the model for inner city
regeneration both in the US and the UK and increasingly in parts of east and
west Europe where urban decline has become a fact of life. In particular, it
is deemed to show that regeneration can be investment rather than grant or
subsidy-led. Taub is very good at analysing the outline of the successes and
the failures of the Bank since it was 'reborn' in 1973. This was when a
group of four non-traditional bankers took over a fully-operating,
neighbourhood bank - albeit in sharp decline - which as Taub describes it
had deposits of Dollars 38m, a conservative staff, and a reputation for not
being very helpful to the new members of the community. The latter phrase is
crucial. South Shore is a typical urban neighbourhood. An area covering
seven by 12 blocks with a population of 75,000, it is sited on the shores of
Lake Michigan. Originally built to house rail workers, it was a traditional,
middle-class Chicago neighbourhood. Unusually, it contains a wide range of
housing from the mansions of Jackson Park Highlands to tenement blocks.
The transition began after the war, when the lack of repairs in South Shore
combined with the temptation of purpose-built housing in the suburbs to
attract local residents to move out.
South Shore proceeded to go through a period of decline with shops closing,
the old infrastructure being torn down, and crime starting to rise. This in
turn increased the outflow of the old population and left South Shore as a
run-down residential area for poor blacks to move into, 50 per cent of whom
had emigrated from the South.
The four managers, who raised the Dollars 3.2m to buy the South Shore Bank,
had all come into banking from differing backgrounds. Their leader was
Ronald Grzywinski, who had grown up within five miles of South Shore and,
after a career with IBM, had joined a local bank where he operated an urban
development division which built up an impressive track record in backing
minority entrepreneurs.
This experience caused him to look at creating a local banking and
investment body with a strong community focus. The original concept was for
the local residents, in addition to investing, to take an increasing role in
running the operation. After some false starts this led the group to
consider buying an existing body. They purchased the bank with a substantial
loan, backed by personal guarantees, and sought to run it like a
conventional bank while remaining true to their commitment to community
values.
Deposits, which now total well over Dollars 100m, were built up by direct
mail to sympathisers all over the US. This new strength was then used to
invest in local projects and businesses. The new regime established a
formula of lending to local property owners and buyers in which they both
stood to gain, by an upturn both in property values and people's
perceptions. The emphasis switched to responsible and careful development
and extended to Minority Enterprise Lending.
In time the bank's holding company was restructured into four divisions: the
bank; a for-profit real estate development company which renovated property
and sold it on; a Minority Enterprise Small Business Investment Company
(Mesbic); and the not-for-profit Neighbourhood Institute which was designed
to cope with the effects of change. The bank is now earning profits of more
than 1.5 per cent of assets.
Where the book is tantalising is that it has a new preface written in 1994
but it is still essentially the text of 1987. It is also light on the actual
lending process - the very area which makes South Shore different.
Nonetheless it is particularly relevant for the apprehensive climate of the
nineties and the need to rebuild.
</TEXT>
<XX>
