<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (11): Something for everyone -
Books on women in management are one of the fastest-growing parts of
business publishing / Female executives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WOMEN IN MANAGEMENT: A DEVELOPING PRESENCE' edited by Morgan Tanton
Routledge, Pounds 14.99, 253 pages
'COMPETITIVE FRONTIERS: WOMEN MANAGERS IN A GLOBAL ECONOMY' edited by Nancy
J. Adler and Dafna N. Izraeli Blackwell, Pounds 19.99, 414 pages
'MASCULINITY AND THE BRITISH ORGANIZATION MAN SINCE 1945' Michael Roper
Oxford University Press, Pounds 25, 259 pages
There are few women in management. Yet there is no shortage of books about
them. While the number of female executives is low and rising imperceptibly
slowly, the number of academics specialising in the field is climbing
steadily, and books on the theme are one of the fastest-growing parts of
management publishing.
The latest crop has something for everyone - from the down-market self-help
books of the 'Dress for Success' variety, to serious academic research. Even
the latter type shows impressive range, from heavy duty feminist rant to
painstaking factual account.
Women in Management, a collection of mainly British research, claims to
represent a 'second generation' of gender studies, and is presented from
what it calls a 'woman-centred perspective'. Editor Morgan Tanton defines
this as follows: 'Instead of highlighting how women are different from men I
have described how women are. I have omitted reference to men or, where this
was unavoidable, I have endeavoured to refer to men as 'other' to the female
norm'.
Such a warning is going to put off a lot of people, (women among them) who
baulk at the idea of any such special perspective. These readers will find
plenty else to offend them in this volume. The token alternative male among
the contributors talks about a revelation that came to him during a
management training session that he was giving.
He realised that his preoccupations as a white male were geared towards
mastering death, whereas those of the black woman who took part in the
session seemed to be more about being at one with the mysteries of life. At
least his account was not followed by three pages of detailed footnotes
quoting other work in the area, as were those of his fellow contributors.
For all its unattractive packaging the collection is not without interest.
One chapter offers a convincing account of the ways in which the supposedly
scientific systems used by companies for appraising their employees may
discriminate against women. Another looks at the differences between male
and female entrepreneurs.
There is a minimum of ideological baggage carried by Competitive Frontiers:
Women Managers in A Global Economy. Instead of concentrating on Britain and
America, whose glass ceilings have already been scrutinised from every
conceivable angle, this collection brings us women managers from all over
the world. The conclusion of the book - that women seem to be struggling to
a more or lesser degree on all continents - is not going to surprise anyone.
The value of the book lies in the bulk of information - presented in a
clear, factual style - about women in countries that for the most part have
escaped detailed examination.
A clear introduction by Nancy Adler summarises in a few pages the last 25
years of research into the barriers facing women managers, and divides the
findings into four categories.
The first are based upon the differences between men and women themselves.
The second take as their focus the organisation, and look at the ways in
which women's under-representation in management can be self perpetuating.
The third involve straightforward discrimination: deeply embedded
assumptions by managers about the role of women. The fourth claim that
male-dominated institutions persist because the people with a vested
interest in their persistance are the ones with the necessary power to make
sure change does not happen.
An interesting new light is cast on the subject by Michael Roper who has
looked at the same subject taking men as his starting point. In Masculinity
and the British Organization Man since 1945 he has interviewed male
corporate veterans and concluded that the idea of male managers as strictly
rational beings is a myth. He has tried to get under the skin of
organisation men by asking them about their relationships with each other,
their wives, their secretaries and their women colleagues.
This is by the the most enjoyable read of the bunch. Each of his subjects is
given a good deal of rope, and nearly all manage to hang themselves with it.
A Mr Dowell, chairman of Hill Components, a traditional engineering company,
starts - as do all the others - by playing lip service to the idea of
promoting women. He then relates the following experience:
'We had a woman engineer who was in charge of all our computer operations
who was extremely good, but eventually became unemployable because. . . she
became more male than the males in her job. She was so aggressive and so
difficult that in the end you couldn't hold a balanced, reasoned argument
with her, because if you said anything that implied criticism of her because
she was a woman, you got the woman bit. So that in the end we had to call it
a day.'
Roper concludes that some aspects of the classic macho manager are under
threat as a result of new technology, restructuring of companies and so.
Whether his demise will bring with it an era of equality is another matter
altogether.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
