<DATE>941102
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (9): High on the agenda - Not
many employers are willing to implement strategic partnerships with trade
unions / Employee relations and workplace reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THE MUTUAL GAINS ENTERPRISE' by Thomas Kochan and Paul Osterman, Harvard
Business School Press, Dollars 27.95, 272 pages
'RESTORING THE PROMISE OF AMERICAN LABOR LAW' edited by Sheldon Friedman,
Richard Hurd, Rudolph Oswald and Ronald Seeber, ILR Press Ithaca, New York.
Dollars 29.95 366 pages
Workplace reform is high on the American labour policy agenda as companies
adapt to the competitive pressures imposed by the global economy. But
whether this will lead to a transformation in corporate America's mainly
adversarial attitude to employee relations must remain doubtful.
Trade unions are now an endangered species. Collective bargaining covers
hardly more than 12 per cent of private sector workers. Organised labour's
influence is minimal on Capitol Hill, as recent decisive defeats indicated
over the North American Free Trade Agreement and the successful Senate
filibuster against legislation making it illegal for companies to hire
replacement workers in strikes. Ten years ago enlightened union leaders
believed human resource management would provide them with a lifeline
because companies would see it was in their competitive advantage to create
more consensual workplaces based on agreements with recognised trade unions.
But these two important and well-written books on the contemporary American
workplace suggest not many employers are willing to introduce strategic
partnerships with trade unions into their own businesses. 'The leading
firms, managers and union leaders that advocate innovative human resource
practices have become islands of innovation in a sea of traditional
practices', lament Professor Tom Kochan and his MIT colleagues.
They believe mere verbal exhortation in favour of 'good' labour practices is
not going to change deep-seated employer attitudes. In their opinion, the
federal government must stimulate more management-labour co-operation,
through what they call the creation of 'a mutual gains coalition'. This
means - they insist - providing a new role for government as 'mediator,
facilitator and enabler of workplace change'.
'The momentum that has built up in the private sector requires government to
become a partner in encouraging investment in human resources and diffusing
the knowledge and innovative practices throughout the American workplace',
argue Kochan and co. No doubt President Clinton's enlightened labour
secretary Robert Reich, a former MIT colleague himself, would agree with
that sentiment but it seems most unlikely it will lead to positive results.
Professor Kochan and his co-authors have produced a sensible, thoughtful and
what ought to be an influential contribution to the public policy debate on
worker representation. The trouble is there are simply not enough companies
willing to listen and act on their conciliatory message.
An important reason for this indifference - they acknowledge - lies in what
they call the 'organisational governance' of the American company. In
Germany and Japan private corporations think and act with their long-term
interests in mind but in the US maximising business performance for the
immediate needs of the shareholders is the primary concern and workplace
change has a low priority to them.
The book calls for 'a new conception of the American corporation' which
would ally shareholder and employee interests more closely together and
building institutions to bring human resource policies into the core of
corporate strategy. The formidable obstacles to American workplace reform
are also well described in the collection of essays from Cornell
University's ILR Press, a fruitful joint product of academia and the AFL-CIO
union federation.
The book asserts bluntly that US workers 'should not be denied the freedom
to associate, to form and join organisations under their own control and of
their own choosing, any more than African-Americans or other minorities
should be denied their civil rights or women equal rights'. And yet this is
what is happening in contemporary America. Apparently it is the 'escalating
use of aggressive union-avoidance tactics' by employers, not any lack of
interest by workers in joining a trade union, that lies at the heart of the
problem. 'A climate of fear now stands in the way of a revival of American
labor unionism', the Cornell study asserts.
The Cornell essays provide a persuasive - sometimes eloquent - argument in
favour of trade unionism as a protection for vulnerable workers in the
labour market - especially women and African-Americans. But many companies
regard trade unions as subversive institutions. This attitude is not new in
US history. Indeed, except for the period between the passage of the 1935
National Labor Relations Act during the New Deal and the early 1960s,
American unions have never found it easy to organise in the face of hostile
employers.
Moreover, as Dorothy Sue Cobble argues in a particularly insightful essay,
the traditional industrial relations system was 'designed for a
mass-production industrial workplace' not today's 'service-dominated,
computer-based global economy'.
As a result, she argues, industrial unionism needs to be replaced by what
she calls 'occupational' unionism, a return to a system that caters for the
needs of workers and employers outside mass production processes as happened
in the US before the 1930s. However, for the vast majority of American
workers non-unionism will remain the dominant fact in the workplace with
little sign that most companies are willing to experiment with other forms
of worker representation as an alternative to trade unionism.
Negotiated workplace change might seem rational commonsense that pays off in
a company's bottom line but a majority of American employers do not believe
this to be self-evident. These books may point the way forward but alas
those who would most benefit from them are the least likely to read them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
