<DOCNO>FT944-12172</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKBD9AGNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941102
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / FT Review of Business Books (8): Railways have fascinating
parallels - Dobbin's examples throw up many fascinating parallels with
present-day thinking on the railways and industry in general / Industrial
policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'FORGING INDUSTRIAL POLICY:  THE US, BRITAIN AND FRANCE IN THE RAILWAY AGE'
By Frank Dobbin Cambridge University Press, Pounds 30, 262 pages
After decades of neglect the railways are once again at the centre of policy
debate in many countries. The privatisation and dismantling of
publicly-owned, centralised rail networks in Europe is leading to a shake-up
of established patterns of operation.
Frank Dobbin's choice of the 19th century railroad industry as the model for
his study of how countries devise their industrial policies is therefore
timely. His examples throw up many fascinating parallels with present-day
thinking on the railways and industry in general although few are explicitly
developed under the historical approach adopted by the author.
Seen against the background of the British parliament's response to the
railroad mania of the 1840s, the present government's much-criticised plans
for a privatised railway network emerge with an impeccable pedigree.
Parliament in the middle of the 19th century left it to private enterprise
to define the public good.
Towards the end of the last century though, as critics of the present
privatisation mania will no doubt point out, these policies had to be
modified. Government intervention became necessary when parliament perceived
that individual property rights - of expropriated landowners  - were under
threat; that passenger safety was at risk and that poorer customers required
protection from the fare policies of greedy railway companies.
But Dobbin, an assistant professor of sociology at Princeton University, has
a far broader canvas. His purpose is to show that the industrial and
economic policies of nations do not conform to a single economic imperative
but reflect the cultures and early industrial experiences from which they
spring.
The railways suit because they were a leading industry which has left
subsequent researchers with a mass of documentary evidence. They were also
one of the earliest sectors which required governments to design a framework
of industrial policies and set a pattern for the treatment of other
industries.
National policies reflect a country's political culture, Dobbin asserts. The
US, Britain and France applied to industrial policy the principles which
they had adopted for their political institutions.
Distrustful of the powers of a strong centralised state, the
newly-independent American colonists determined to vest power in the
individual communities and states while restraining the powers of central
government.
But this approach had to be modified when local and state schemes to promote
railroad construction led to frauds and scandals. The result was the
creation of the Interstate Commerce Commission to impose federal regulation
and prevent anti-competitive practices. The federal government was still
kept at a distance but an anti-trust framework was put in place to ensure
fair play and maximum economic advantage.
If the Americans turned the state into the referee of the free market, the
French, in contrast, saw the state as the conductor of the industrial
orchestra.
They regarded a centralised, professional state bureaucracy as necessary for
public order. So when it came to designing a railway network it was only
natural for the state and its technical experts to decide routes and
systems. To allow competing private entrepreneurs to have their way would
have wasted resources and posed a threat to good political and economic
order.
The British approach, while superficially similar to that adopted by the
Americans in its reliance on private enterprise, was different in important
respects, Dobbin argues. After initially taking a completely laisser faire
stance, parliament was forced to intervene to protect, not the market, on
the American model, but the individual entrepreneur.
By the end of the 19th century, policies were designed to shield the
entrepreneurial small company from the vagaries of politics and the market.
Ultimately this led to British industrial policies, including subsidies,
production quotas and price fixing, which did much to contribute to the
country's industrial decline.
But whatever may have happened in more recent times, in the 19th century, at
least, the three different national approaches to railways policy all had
the effect of producing 'rapid, dependable and cost-effective transport
systems in relatively short order. No strategy failed in any important
sense.'
Observers of the business scene might disagree with Dobbin's assertion that
the British treat their small companies better than their continental
European rivals, although this may be a more recent development. They might
also take issue with the view that subsidy and protection are peculiarly
British phenomena.
Some readers might feel that the author's failure to take into account the
radical changes in economic policies which have shaken up the UK and the
other economies of Europe in the past 15 years represent the book's main
weakness.
But equally irritating is the turgid, jargon-packed style of the opening and
closing sections where he elaborates his theories. Some readers may be
deterred from turning to the country studies which make up the more easily
accessible core of the book.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
