<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets: Brazil falls by 2%
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Concern about November inflation and a possible further increase in nominal
interest rates dragged stock prices down for the second day in a row to
close 2.02 per cent lower yesterday.
Trading was sluggish since most investors were out of the market ahead of
the All Saints Day holiday today, when Brazil's markets are closed. The
Bovespa index retreated a further 970 points to 47,009.
Investors were worried about forecasts that the November inflation rate
could reach 3 per cent after a 1.9 per cent rise in October.
US investment bank Merrill Lynch has reduced its portfolio weighting in
Latin American markets in view of the gains shown since the summer and their
'historic sensitivity to sharp movements in US interest rates'. It said
Brazil faced a difficult few months ahead and the change in government could
mark a correction from recent gains. The bank has increased its portfolio
weightings in Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia and Japan.
